ὓ Valentinus was abbot of the monastery at Hadrumetum, the capital of Byzacenum (now Sousse‚ 100 miles south of Tunis). Two of his monks, Florus and Felix, when visiting the monastery at L‘zala‚ read and copied Augustine's letter to the presbyter Sixtus (Ep. cxciv.) on grace and free-will, and on their return to Adrumetum read it to the monks there, some of whom considered Augustine's teaching fatal to the doctrine of free-will. The monastery was bitterly divided on the question, so Valentinus sent Felix and Cresconius, another of the disputants, to ascertain Augustine’s real opinions. The present letter is his reply.
